#X text 24 22 This chapter focuses on Amplitude and Frequency modulation \, but incorporated into a broader concept of modulation synthesis that combines them. In fact \, both of them highlight the term modulation \, but we have also seen modulation in the other previous topics. Hence \, let's clear things out as what it all means., f 55;
#X text 24 117 In generally \, modulating a signal means applying any changes to it. In the context of computer music and synthesis \, we're talking about a modulating signal that controls a parameter \, such as amplitude \, frequency \, filter cuttof \, pulse width or whatever. As such \, for the additive synthesis examples we did have frequency and amplitude modulation \, but as 'low frequency'. In a similar fashion \, for wavetable synthesis we had an example of low frequency random modulation to scan the waveforms. As for Subtractive Synthesis we've seen filter modulation with envelopes \, LFOs and low frequency noise... What makes this chapter is that we now have "high frequency" modulation., f 55;
#X text 24 309 Nonetheless \, one can technically consider low frequency modulation of amplitude and frequency as a sort of modulation as there is no term to differentiate between them. Hence \, for starters \, let's revisit an addtive synthesis example with low random frequency modulation of both frequncy and amplitude of every partial., f 55;
